<SECTION1 LBL="" HELPID = ""><TITLE><XREFTARGET ID="74943">Planning the Physical Network</TITLE><PARAGRAPH>Planning the physical network requires that you first answer the question, &ldquo;What network media and topology configuration would best suit the needs of my users?&rdquo; A review of the MAC (Medium Access Control) level and application-level performance information about the products you are considering will help you determine the appropriate choice of media for your environment. In your review, consider the size (number of stations) of your network. Your network size will influence the media type and topology you choose for your network. If your network requires different types of media, determine whether you have the correct equipment for integrating the various media types.<INDEXTARGET ID="02.planning1"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: 02.planning1|network planning: size considerations --><INDEXTARGET ID="02.planning2"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: 02.planning2|planning: network size --></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>These subsections will help you answer this list of planning questions:</PARAGRAPH>
<BULLETLIST><BULLET><PARAGRAPH>What will my physical network look like? See <XREF IDREF="17528" TYPE="TITLE">&ldquo;About Repeaters, Bridges, Routers, and Gateways&rdquo;</XREF>.</PARAGRAPH>
</BULLET>
<BULLET><PARAGRAPH>Do I have a map of my network? For an example, see<XREF IDREF="44236" TYPE="TITLE">&ldquo;About Wide Area Networks&rdquo;</XREF>.</PARAGRAPH>
</BULLET>
<BULLET><PARAGRAPH>Will I need a repeater, bridge, router, or gateway? See <XREF IDREF="17528" TYPE="TITLE">&ldquo;About Repeaters, Bridges, Routers, and Gateways&rdquo;</XREF>.</PARAGRAPH>
</BULLET>
<BULLET><PARAGRAPH>Will this network configuration meet my users' needs? See <XREF IDREF="45513" TYPE="TITLE">&ldquo;About Network Performance&rdquo;</XREF>.</PARAGRAPH>
</BULLET>
<BULLET><PARAGRAPH>Where are my performance bottlenecks? Can I reduce or avoid them? See <XREF IDREF="45513" TYPE="TITLE">&ldquo;About Network Performance&rdquo;</XREF>.</PARAGRAPH>
</BULLET>
</BULLETLIST>
<SECTION2 LBL="" HELPID = ""><TITLE><XREFTARGET ID="17528">About Repeaters, Bridges, Routers, and Gateways</TITLE><PARAGRAPH>Your choice of media and the number of stations, networks, and protocols in your network may require the use of a repeater, bridge, router, or gateway. This section suggests the type of device required for certain network functions.<INDEXTARGET ID="02.planning3"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: 02.planning3|network equipment, planning --><INDEXTARGET ID="02.planning4"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: 02.planning4|planning: network equipment --></PARAGRAPH>
<HANGLIST><HANGPAIR><HANGITEM><ITALICS>repeate</ITALICS>r</HANGITEM>
<HANGBODY><PARAGRAPH>A device that regenerates and amplifies electrical signals. Its purpose is to extend the physical length of a network.<INDEXTARGET ID="02.planning5"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: 02.planning5|repeater, definition of --></PARAGRAPH>
</HANGBODY>
</HANGPAIR>
<HANGPAIR><HANGITEM><ITALICS>bridge</ITALICS></HANGITEM>
<HANGBODY><PARAGRAPH>A device that decodes MAC-layer frames transmitted between different hardware and media. Its purpose is to resolve network media differences; it allows a network to be composed of various media types (Ethernet, fiber, serial, and so on). It can also be used to segment similar media types and provide segment isolation for lower network traffic.<INDEXTARGET ID="02.planning6"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: 02.planning6|bridge, definition of --></PARAGRAPH>
</HANGBODY>
</HANGPAIR>
<HANGPAIR><HANGITEM><ITALICS>router</ITALICS></HANGITEM>
<HANGBODY><PARAGRAPH>A device that decodes and passes network-layer packets between different networks. Its purpose is to provide the physical and logical route from one network to another.<INDEXTARGET ID="02.planning7"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: 02.planning7|router, definition of --></PARAGRAPH>
</HANGBODY>
</HANGPAIR>
<HANGPAIR><HANGITEM><ITALICS>gateway</ITALICS></HANGITEM>
<HANGBODY><PARAGRAPH>A device that translates protocols from one station to another. Its purpose is to allow stations with different networking protocols to communicate successfully.<INDEXTARGET ID="02.planning8"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: 02.planning8|gateway, definition of --></PARAGRAPH>
</HANGBODY>
</HANGPAIR>
</HANGLIST>
<NOTE><PREFIX>Note</PREFIX>The terms <ITALICS>router</ITALICS> and <ITALICS>gateway</ITALICS> are sometimes used interchangeably. Be sure you know the function of the device you are considering, because the term may be technically inaccurate.</NOTE>
<PARAGRAPH>Note that each device may not be limited to a single function. For example, a gateway may also perform router functions if it is configured as a router. <XREF IDREF="98698" TYPE="TABLE">Table&nbsp;2-1</XREF> summarizes the characteristics of each network device.</PARAGRAPH>
